root="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>1641</fr:anchor><fr:taxon>Theorem</fr:taxon><fr:addr>axt-000H</fr:addr><fr:route>axt-000H.xml</fr:route><fr:source-path>/Users/ayberkt/Code/mathematical-forest/trees/public/axt-000H.tree</fr:source-path><fr:date><fr:year>2023</fr:year><fr:month>9</fr:month><fr:day>4</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author>Ayberk Tosun</fr:author></fr:authors><fr:last-changed><fr:date><fr:year>2024</fr:year><fr:month>1</fr:month><fr:day>9</fr:day></fr:date></fr:last-changed></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>A space <fr:tex>X</fr:tex> has <fr:link
href="axt-000E.xml"
type="local"
addr="axt-000E">no separation</fr:link> iff its only clopen subsets are the trivial ones.</fr:p><fr:p><fr:tex>( \Rightarrow )</fr:tex> Suppose space <fr:tex>X</fr:tex> has no separation and let <fr:tex>F  \subseteq  X</fr:tex>
  be a clopen. Suppose, towards a contradiction, that <fr:tex>F</fr:tex> is a nontrivial
  subset i.e. it is neither <fr:tex>\empty</fr:tex> nor <fr:tex>X</fr:tex>. Denote by <fr:tex>F^{-1}</fr:tex> the
  complement of <fr:tex>F</fr:tex> in <fr:tex>X</fr:tex>. The set <fr:tex>F^{-1}</fr:tex> must be clopen and disjoint from
  <fr:tex>F</fr:tex> by definition. Because <fr:tex>F  \neq  X</fr:tex>, it must exclude some point <fr:tex>x  \in    X</fr:tex>, which must be contained by <fr:tex>F^{-1}</fr:tex> by construction. This means <fr:tex>F^{-1}</fr:tex>
  is nonempty. Therefore, the pair <fr:tex>(F, F^{-1})</fr:tex> is a separation of the space
  <fr:tex>X</fr:tex>: <fr:tex>X = F  \cup  F^{-1}</fr:tex>, both <fr:tex>F</fr:tex> and <fr:tex>F^{-1}</fr:tex> are nonempty, and they
  are disjoint from each other. This contradicts the assumption <fr:tex>X</fr:tex> has no
  separation.
</fr:p><fr:p><fr:tex>( \Leftarrow )</fr:tex> Suppose the only clopen subsets of space <fr:tex>X</fr:tex> are the trivial
  ones i.e. <fr:tex>\empty</fr:tex> and <fr:tex>X</fr:tex>. Suppose <fr:tex>X</fr:tex> had a separation <fr:tex>(U, V)</fr:tex>. Then
  <fr:tex>V</fr:tex> must be the complement of <fr:tex>U</fr:tex> in <fr:tex>X</fr:tex>. This means that it must be
  closed, by virtue of being the complement of an open <fr:tex>U</fr:tex>. Also, the open <fr:tex>U</fr:tex>
  must be closed too since it is itself the complement of the open <fr:tex>V</fr:tex>. As
  both <fr:tex>U</fr:tex> and <fr:tex>V</fr:tex> are both nonempty, they both cannot be either <fr:tex>\empty</fr:tex> or
  <fr:tex>X</fr:tex>. This means they are both nontrivial clopens.
</fr:p></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree></fr:context><fr:related></fr:related><fr:backlinks></fr:backlinks><fr:references></fr:references></fr:backmatter></fr:tree>